  1. Tidy up the data ready for regression:
  • You might like to think about removing some or all of date, id, sqft_living15, sqft_lot15 and zipcode (lat and long provide a better measure of location in any event).
  • Have a think about how to treat waterfront. Should we convert its type?
  • We converted yr_renovated into a renovated logical variable, indicating whether the property had ever been renovated. You may wish to do the same.
  • Have a think about how to treat condition and grade? Are they interval or categorical ordinal data types?

mutate(view = as.logical(waterfront)) %>%

library(tidyverse) 
library(janitor) 
library(lubridate) 
library(modelr) 
library(GGally) 

houses <- read_csv("data/kc_house_data.csv") %>% 
  select(-c(id, sqft_living15, sqft_lot15, zipcode, date, sqft_above)) %>% 
  mutate(waterfront = as.logical(waterfront)) %>% 
  mutate(yr_renovated = as.logical(yr_renovated)) 

 Column specification 
cols(
  .default = col_double(),
  id = col_character(),
  date = col_datetime(format = "")
)
 Use `spec()` for the full column specifications.
houses
  1. Check for aliased variables using the alias() function (this takes in a formula object and a data set). [Hint - formula price ~ . says price varying with all predictors, this is a suitable input to alias()]. Remove variables that lead to an alias. Check the Elements of multiple regression lesson for a dropdown containing further information on finding aliased variables in a dataset.
model_alias <- lm(price ~ ., data = houses) 

alias(model_alias) 
Model :
price ~ bedrooms + bathrooms + sqft_living + sqft_lot + floors + 
    waterfront + view + condition + grade + sqft_basement + yr_built + 
    yr_renovated + lat + long
  1. Systematically build a regression model containing up to four main effects (remember, a main effect is just a single predictor with coefficient),testing the regression diagnostics as you go.
  • Splitting datasets into numeric and non-numeric columns might help ggpairs() run in manageable time, although you will need to add either a price or resid column to the non-numeric dataframe in order to see its correlations with the non-numeric predictors.
houses_numeric <- houses %>% 
  select(price, bedrooms, bathrooms, sqft_living, sqft_lot, sqft_basement, 
         floors, condition, grade, yr_built, lat, long, view) 

ggpairs(houses_numeric) 

houses_nonnumeric <- houses_clean %>% 
  select_if(function(x) !is.numeric(x)) 

houses_nonnumeric 

houses_nonnumeric$price <- houses_clean$price 

ggpairs(houses_nonnumeric)

Square foot of the living space - price increases by 280 for each increase in square foot. It accounts for 49% of variance in price.

model_1 <- lm(price ~ sqft_living, data = houses)

Searching for the predictors not yet in our model by adding the residuals.

remaining_residuals <- houses %>% 
  add_residuals(model_1) %>% 
  select(-c("price", "sqft_living")) 

remaining_residuals %>% 
  ggpairs()
